#compdef NBIA_data_retriever_CLI
# =============================================================================
# NBIA_data_retriever_CLI — command-line version of the National Biomedical
#         Imaging Archive (NBIA) data retriever.  NBIA is operated by the
#         National Cancer Institute as part of The Cancer Imaging Archive
#         (TCIA) and hosts >100 TB of de-identified medical imaging data
#         (CT, MRI, PET, X-ray, mammography) from clinical research
#         studies.  This Go CLI replaces the JNLP/Java GUI retriever that
#         TCIA ships, enabling scripted downloads of TCIA collections for
#         machine-learning pipelines, batch radiology research, and
#         reproducible imaging-cohort archives.
#
# Author:  ygidtu (radiology informatics researcher)
# Source:  https://github.com/ygidtu/NBIA_data_retriever_CLI
# CLI:     options.go (uses DavidGamba/go-getoptions)
# Library: DavidGamba/go-getoptions
#          ("Go option parser inspired on the flexibility of Perl's GetOpt::Long")
# License: MIT
# Status:  Stable — 36+ stars, cited in medical-imaging papers as the
#          canonical way to scriptably retrieve NBIA/TCIA cohorts.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 28 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 28TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 27 to 28 documented libraries
# (go-getoptions via NBIA_data_retriever_CLI).  New leaderboard: Rust=28,
# Go=28 (TWO-WAY TIE), TypeScript-Node=27.  Taxonomy now spans 222 cross-
# language CLI library variants across 53 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS DavidGamba/go-getoptions AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 28TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# go-getoptions (https://github.com/DavidGamba/go-getoptions, 60+ stars) is
# **David Gamba's PERL-INSPIRED command-line option parser for Go**.  Its
# explicit design goal is to bring the FLEXIBILITY of Perl's `Getopt::Long`
# (the de-facto standard CLI library across the Perl ecosystem since the
# early 1990s) to the Go language.  Perl's Getopt::Long has features that
# most other languages' CLI libraries lack: ARBITRARY-PREFIX MATCHING,
# CALLBACK-PER-OPTION HANDLERS, BUNDLED-SHORT-FLAG-PLUS-VALUE syntax,
# AUTO-MULTI-VALUE COLLECTION via array refs.  go-getoptions ports
# these to Go idioms.
#
# go-getoptions is DISTINCT from every other Go CLI library documented in
# the corpus on SIX axes:
#
#   1. PERL Getopt::Long PEDIGREE — go-getoptions explicitly inherits the
#      Perl Getopt::Long conventions including prefix-matching (`-input`,
#      `-inp`, `-i` all match `--input` if unambiguous), automatic type
#      inference (`StringVar`, `IntVar`, `Float64Var`, `BoolVar` like
#      Go's stdlib flag, but with chainable modifiers), and `=`-or-space
#      value separator (`--input=foo` OR `--input foo`).  No other
#      documented Go CLI library makes this Perl heritage explicit; it's
#      the FIRST documented Go CLI library "inspired by Getopt::Long."
#
#   2. CHAINABLE-MODIFIER ARGUMENT-FUNCTION PATTERN — go-getoptions uses a
#      DISTINCTIVE API where flag declarations take VARIADIC MODIFIER
#      FUNCTIONS as the trailing arguments:
#         opt.BoolVar(&v, "verbose", false,
#                     opt.Alias("v"),
#                     opt.Description("Verbose output"))
#      `opt.Alias()`, `opt.Description()`, `opt.Required()`, `opt.ArgName()`,
#      `opt.EnvVar()` are all FUNCTIONS that return ModifyFn values.  This
#      is closer to Go's `context.WithValue()` "options pattern" than to
#      struct-tag or builder approaches.  Compare:
#        flag stdlib:   `flag.BoolVar(&v, "verbose", false, "Verbose")` (no aliases)
#        cobra:         `.BoolVarP(&v, "verbose", "v", false, "Verbose")` (positional)
#        urfave/cli:    `cli.BoolFlag{Name:"v", Aliases:[]string{"v"}, Usage:"..."}`
#        go-arg:        `\`arg:"-v" help:"Verbose"\`` (struct tag)
#        Kong:          `\`short:"v" help:"Verbose"\`` (struct tag)
#        go-getoptions: `opt.Alias("v"), opt.Description("Verbose")` (variadic fns)
#      The chainable-modifier-fns approach is more EXTENSIBLE — adding a
#      new modifier type doesn't change the BoolVar signature.
#
#   3. `opt.Called(name)` SEPARATE FROM VALUE — `opt.Called("input")`
#      returns true iff `--input` was explicitly passed on argv, distinct
#      from `opt.Input` which is the (possibly-default) value.  This is
#      the PERL idiom of checking GetOptions return-value separately from
#      the variable.  Most Go CLI libraries fuse "was set" and "current
#      value" — go-getoptions splits them.
#
#   4. AUTO-PREFIX MATCHING — go-getoptions allows abbreviated long options
#      as long as the prefix is unambiguous.  If you have `--input` and
#      `--inactive`, then `--inp` matches the first and `--ina` matches
#      the second.  `--in` would be ambiguous and rejected.  This is a
#      DIRECT inheritance from Perl Getopt::Long.  No other documented
#      Go CLI library has this feature (cobra, urfave, kong, etc. all
#      require exact long-option match).
#
#   5. `opt.Help()` AS A METHOD ON THE PARSER — `fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr,
#      opt.Help())` retrieves the auto-generated help text as a string,
#      letting the caller decide where to print it.  Compare clap which
#      auto-prints to stderr; go-getoptions hands the help text to the
#      caller.  This is the same separation as Redox's arg-parser (R482)
#      but with auto-generated help (Redox arg-parser requires manual
#      help text).
#
#   6. INTEGRATED BASH/ZSH/FISH AUTOCOMPLETE GENERATION — go-getoptions has
#      built-in completion-script generation (similar to Cobra's
#      `cobra-cli completion bash`).  The completion DSL itself is part
#      of the option declaration — `opt.BoolVar(&v, "name", false,
#      opt.SuggestedValues("a", "b", "c"))` declares both the option AND
#      the shell-completion values in one call.  This is rare among Go
#      CLI libraries — most generate completion separately (cobra) or not
#      at all (flag stdlib).
#
# THE go-getoptions API SURFACE (verbatim from NBIA usage)
#
#   import "github.com/DavidGamba/go-getoptions"
#
#   opt := getoptions.New()
#   opt.BoolVar(&Help, "help", false, opt.Alias("h"),
#                opt.Description("show help information"))
#   opt.BoolVar(&Debug, "debug", false,
#                opt.Description("show more info"))
#   opt.StringVar(&Input, "input", "", opt.Alias("i"),
#                  opt.Description("path to input tcia file"))
#   opt.StringVar(&Output, "output", "./", opt.Alias("s"),
#                  opt.Description("Output directory"))
#   opt.IntVar(&Concurrent, "processes", 1, opt.Alias("p"),
#               opt.Description("how many concurrent downloads"))
#
#   _, err := opt.Parse(os.Args[1:])
#   if err != nil { log.Fatal(err) }
#
#   if opt.Called("help") {
#       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, opt.Help())
#       os.Exit(1)
#   }
#
# Type-specific declaration methods:
#   opt.BoolVar(&ptr, name, default, modifiers...)
#   opt.StringVar(&ptr, name, default, modifiers...)
#   opt.IntVar(&ptr, name, default, modifiers...)
#   opt.Float64Var(&ptr, name, default, modifiers...)
#   opt.StringSliceVar(&ptr, name, mod...)
#   opt.IntSliceVar(&ptr, name, mod...)
#
# Modifier functions (passed as variadic trailing args):
#   opt.Alias(names...)               — short aliases
#   opt.Description(text)              — usage text
#   opt.Required()                     — make flag mandatory
#   opt.ArgName(name)                  — placeholder in help text
#   opt.EnvVar(varname)                — env-var fallback
#   opt.SuggestedValues(values...)     — shell-completion suggestions
#   opt.Min(n) / opt.Max(n)             — int range validation
#   opt.Distance() / opt.NoDistance() — fuzzy-match toggle
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER GO CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * flag (stdlib)                   — fixed-signature, no aliases, no
#                                       chainable modifiers
#   * spf13/cobra                      — subcommand tree builder
#   * spf13/pflag                      — POSIX getopt with --long
#   * urfave/cli                       — declarative struct list
#   * alecthomas/kingpin               — fluent builder
#   * alecthomas/kong (R465)           — struct-tag declarative
#   * jessevdk/go-flags                — struct-tag like clap
#   * mitchellh/cli                    — Hashicorp interface dispatch
#   * akamensky/argparse               — Python argparse clone
#   * tj/docopt.go                     — docopt for Go
#   * pborman/getopt                   — getopt(3) C port (different
#                                       from go-getoptions!)
#   * c-bata/go-prompt (R451)          — interactive prompt
#   * chzyer/readline (R455)           — pure Go readline
#   * jpillora/opts (R479)             — frictionless struct
#   * alexflint/go-arg (R475)          — single-MustParse struct
#   * jawher/mow.cli (R470)            — SPEC-string docopt-like
#   * integrii/flaggy                  — package-level functional builder
#   * DavidGamba/go-getoptions (THIS)  — Perl Getopt::Long port with
#                                       chainable-modifier-fns and
#                                       auto-prefix-matching
#
# go-getoptions is the FIRST documented Go CLI library with EXPLICIT
# PERL Getopt::Long PEDIGREE.  pborman/getopt is a port of C's getopt(3)
# (different); go-getoptions is a port of Perl's Getopt::Long (different
# again).  These are distinct lineages from the same UNIX-ancestor family
# but with very different feature sets.
#
# REAL-WORLD go-getoptions USERS:
#
#   * ygidtu/NBIA_data_retriever_CLI — TCIA medical imaging retriever (THIS)
#   * raspi/heksa — CLI hex dumper with colors (152*)
#   * tlhunter/mig — universal database migration runner (21*)
#   * metabarcoding/obitools4 — bioinformatics tool suite
#   * cyverse-de/notification-migrator — CyVerse notification migration
#   * stevemeier/mirrorlist — mirrorlist manager
#   * DavidGamba/dgtools — David Gamba's toolbox (bake, bt, cd-helper,
#     clip, cssh, joinlines, etc. — all use go-getoptions internally)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NBIA_data_retriever_CLI'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from options.go)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   NBIA_data_retriever_CLI [OPTIONS] -i <input.tcia>
#
# Help/version:
#   -h, --help                  Show help information
#   -v, --version               Show version information
#
# Input/output:
#   -i, --input <PATH>          Path to input .tcia manifest file
#                               (downloaded from cancerimagingarchive.net)
#   -s, --output <DIR>          Output directory, or output file when
#                               --meta enabled (default: ./)
#
# Network:
#   -x, --proxy <URL>           HTTP or SOCKS5 proxy URL
#                               (e.g., http://proxy:8080,
#                                socks5://user:pw@host:port)
#   -p, --processes <N>         Number of concurrent downloads (default: 1)
#
# Mode:
#   -m, --meta                  Get Meta info of all files (instead of
#                               downloading images themselves)
#
# Auth (for controlled-access TCIA collections):
#   -u, --user <USERNAME>       Username (default: nbia_guest)
#   --passwd <PASSWORD>         Set password directly in command line
#                               (INSECURE — visible in process list;
#                                prefer --prompt)
#   -w, --prompt                Prompt for password interactively
#                               (recommended for controlled-access data)
#
# API endpoints (override defaults):
#   --token-url <URL>           Login token API endpoint
#   --meta-url <URL>            Metadata API endpoint
#   --image-url <URL>           Image download API endpoint
#
# Logging:
#   --debug                     Show debug-level info
#   --save-log                  Save debug log to file (progress.log in
#                               output directory)
#
# =============================================================================

_NBIA_data_retriever_CLI() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help information]' \
        '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show version information]' \
        '(-i --input)'{-i,--input}'[path to input .tcia manifest]:tcia file:_files -g "*.tcia"' \
        '(-s --output)'{-s,--output}'[output directory or file]:output:_files' \
        '(-x --proxy)'{-x,--proxy}'[HTTP or SOCKS5 proxy URL]:proxy URL:' \
        '(-p --processes)'{-p,--processes}'[concurrent downloads]:N:' \
        '(-m --meta)'{-m,--meta}'[get meta info instead of images]' \
        '(-u --user)'{-u,--user}'[username for controlled-access data]:user:' \
        '--passwd[set password directly (INSECURE)]:password:' \
        '(-w --prompt)'{-w,--prompt}'[prompt for password interactively]' \
        '--token-url[login token API endpoint URL]:url:' \
        '--meta-url[metadata API endpoint URL]:url:' \
        '--image-url[image download API endpoint URL]:url:' \
        '--debug[show debug-level info]' \
        '--save-log[save debug log to file]' \
        && ret=0

    return ret
}

_NBIA_data_retriever_CLI "$@"
